main event: An unidentified object was sighted by military pilots from the 99th Bomb Wing, maintaining a parallel course and appearing as a small, silvery, and celestial object, which was later identified as the planet Venus.
interesting points: The sighting occurred at an approximate location of 560 miles East of Resolution Island in 1952.
The object was initially identified as the planet Venus due to its navigational turns, indicating celestial movement.
The encounter lasted for 10-15 minutes, with the object being observed at varying elevations between 9,000 and 13,000 feet altitude.
Aircraft from the 99th Bomb Wing maneuvered between 330 and 260 degrees to keep the object in sight for over an hour.
Astro pilots indicated the position of Venus to confirm the celestial identification.
result: Celestial identification - later confirmed to be the planet Venus
location: Approx. 560 mi East of Resolution Island
witnesses: Military pilots from the 99th Bomb Wing
photographs: No photographs included in the report
